declarations.description:
Alert groups are containers for a set of alerts. Alert groups can hold one or many alerts
inside of them with the expectation that all alerts will be of the same type. The exception
to this rule is the `loading` alert type, which will be displayed regardless of the type
of alert group containing it.

```typescript
import '@cds/core/alert/register.js';
```

```html
  <cds-alert-group type="danger">
    <cds-alert closable="true">
      Single alert
      <cds-alert-actions>
        buttons, links
      </cds-alert-actions>
    </cds-alert>
    <cds-alert type="loading">
      Single Alert
    </cds-alert>
    <cds-alert closable="true">
      Another alert
      <cds-alert-actions>
        buttons, links
      </cds-alert-actions>
    </cds-alert>
  </cds-alert-group>
```

declarations.description:
Alerts are banners that communicate a message with a severity attached to it.
They grab the userâ€™s attention to provide critical information needed in context.

Alerts outside of a cds-alert-group or cds-app-alert-group component will be
displayed as a "lightweight alert". Lightweight alerts, by default, provide no
close button component and they inherit no status (a.k.a. success, danger, etc.).

Alerts inside a cds-alert-group component inherit their status from the containing
alert group.

Alerts inside a cds-app-alert-group component inherit their status as a default from
the containing app-alert group, although it can be overridden on individual alerts.

```typescript
import '@cds/core/alert/register.js';
```

```html
  <cds-alert>
    Single Alert
    <cds-alert-actions>
      buttons, links
    </cds-alert-actions>
  </cds-alert>
```

slots.description: Content slot for inside the button

members.name: action
members.description:
Define the type of action the button triggers

- `solid`: buttons direct the userâ€™s attention to the primary action the application is suggesting that the user take.
- `outline`: buttons indicate secondary actions that compliments a primary action or reduces visual noise when there are many actions on the page.
- `flat`: buttons are used as tertiary buttons. Can also be used inline because they are different from content in style and recognizable as buttons alongside content.

members.name: status
members.description: Sets the color of the button to match the following string statuses

members.name: size
members.description: Sets the overall height and width of the button based on the following string values:

members.name: block
members.description: Sets if the button should be full width with display block

members.name: loadingState
members.description:
`default`: shows the content of the button
- `loading`: disables the button and shows a spinner inside the button
- `success`: disables the button and shows a check mark inside the button; auto-triggers to change back to DEFAULT state after 1000 ms
- `error`: shows the content of the button (in the context of application, this state is usually entered from a LOADING state. the application should show appropriate error message)

members.name: emulateActiveMouseDown
members.description:
This mimics the mouse-click visual behavior for keyboard only users and screen readers.
Browsers do not apply the CSS psuedo-selector :active in those instances. So we need this
for our :active styles to show.

Make sure to update a component's CSS to account for the presence of the [_active] attribute
in all instance where :active is defined.

members.name: triggerNativeButtonBehavior
members.description:
We have to append a hidden button outside the web component in the light DOM
This allows us to trigger native submit events within a form element.

members.name: associateNonGroupRadios
members.description:
Native radio inputs have no concept of an un-checked event. This means for
our radios to update/rerender we need to listen for the other radios in the
group when the are checked. If the Radio is within a cds-control-group or
cds-radio-group then the group handles this. Radios can be used outside of
groups in cases of using aria-labelledby like a selectable grid row/cell.

members.name: color

members.name: closable
members.description:
If present, shows a close icon to one side of the tag.
Note that applications must wire up the action to remove the tag on click and also
that you cannot have a clickable AND closable tag. The closable attribute-property
shows the close icon. What happens when the tag is clicked is for application developers
to decide.
If closable is present, the tag will be considered "clickable".

members.name: treeItemLeftHandSideTemplate
members.description:
This container contains one of the following depending on the state of the tree item:
  - caret if the tree item is expandable
  - progress circle if the tree item is loading its children (via an async call, etc)
  - nothing if the tree item is an end node

The container with a fixed width ensures the same alignment whether or not it contains
a child elemeent to render.

members.name: emulateActiveMouseDown
members.description:
This mimics the mouse-click visual behavior for keyboard only users and screen readers.
Browsers do not apply the CSS psuedo-selector :active in those instances. So we need this
for our :active styles to show.

Make sure to update a component's CSS to account for the presence of the [_active] attribute
in all instance where :active is defined.

members.name: triggerNativeButtonBehavior
members.description:
We have to append a hidden button outside the web component in the light DOM
This allows us to trigger native submit events within a form element.

members.description:
Its recommended to remove or add a focus trap element from the DOM
some SSR systems can have technical constraints where the item can
only be removed via CSS/hidden.

declarations.name: globalStyle
declarations.description:
Appends a global `<style>` tag to the light DOM of a given custom element.
This is useful for when styles need to be applied that are not supported
withing a `::slotted()` selector such as ::-vendor style selectors.

A property decorator which accesses a set of string values for use
inside the element's template. The values can be overridden at runtime
by changing the property value that's reflected through the attribute value.

members.description:
keycodes() returns a clone of the key codes dictionary/hashmap, not the actual registry.
Performing actions on the return value of the keycodes getter will not be reflected in the
actual keycodes dictionary!

declarations.name: sleep
declarations.description:
sleep() is used in animation code and also in some unit tests where async behavior needs to
be tested.

Use sleep() inside an async function to delay execution for a short period of time.

```
async function ohai() {
   await sleep(55); // delays execution by at least 55 ms
   return 'ohai';
}
```

NOTE: the time sent to sleep is the MINIMUM time duration to execution. It is not and will not
be the exact time to execution.

declarations.name: isFocusable
declarations.description:
We are not going to be opinionated about the use of the disabled attribute here.
Browsers will manage that on their own. The focus of this is to determine whether
or not a tabindex should be set on an element to make it programmatically
focusable.

declarations.description: Coerces attribute/property value to a boolean

declarations.name: keyWasEvented
declarations.description: keyWasEvented() checks to see if a given key is part of any KeyboardEvent it is passed.

declarations.name: onKey
declarations.description:
onKey() takes a single key and fires a handler if that key is part of
the KeyboardEvent it was passed.

declarations.name: onAnyKey
declarations.description:
onAnyKey() takes an array of keys and fires a handler if any of the keys are part of
the KeyboardEvent it was passed.

declarations.name: onKeyCombo
declarations.description:
onKeyCombo() takes a string representation of a combination of keys and modifier keys such as
'ctrl+shift+a'.

onKeyCombo() does not make accommodation for the '+' symbol in a key combo. Consider using 'ctrl+shift+='.

onKeyCombo() accounts for 'cmd', 'win', and 'meta' keys inside keycombos. 'cmd+K', 'win+K', and 'meta+K'
are all the same thing to onKeyCombo().

declarations.name: getModifierKeysFromKeyCombo
declarations.description:
getModifierKeysFromKeyCombo() takes a keycombo string and returns an array with all of the
special keys in the keycombo.

declarations.name: removeModifierKeysFromKeyCombo
declarations.description:
removeModifierKeysFromKeyCombo() takes a keycombo string and returns an array with all of the
non-special keys in the keycombo.

members.name: associateNonGroupRadios
members.description:
Native radio inputs have no concept of an un-checked event. This means for
our radios to update/rerender we need to listen for the other radios in the
group when the are checked. If the Radio is within a cds-control-group or
cds-radio-group then the group handles this. Radios can be used outside of
groups in cases of using aria-labelledby like a selectable grid row/cell.
